Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{0.25%tsp} for the rice.

When boiling, add the @basmati rice{150%g} and cook for ~{12%minutes}. Drain in a
#sieve{}, pop back in the pan, cover with a #lid{} and leave to the side until
ready to serve.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced).

Halve the @green pepper{1}(halved, core and seeds discarded) and discard the core
and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Heat a splash of @oil{1%splash} in a large #frying pan{} over high heat.

When the oil is hot, add the @beef strips{240%g}.

Sprinkle on the @thai style spice mix{1%package} (see ingredients for amounts -
be careful it's hot!) and stir-fry until browned but not cooked through, ~{2%mins}.

TIP: Do this in batches if your pan is small. You want the steak to brown not stew.

Transfer to a #plate{}, wipe out the pan and return to high heat with a splash
of @oil{1%splash}.

IMPORTANT: The steak is safe to eat when the outside is cooked.

When the oil is hot, stir-fry the red onions and peppers until slightly
softened, ~{2-3%mins}.

Lower the heat and stir in the @hoisin sauce{64%g} and @soy sauce{25%ml}.

Bring to a bubble and remove from the heat.

While the rice cooks, return the pan to medium heat and stir in the beef strips
you browned earlier.

Pour in any steak resting juices.

Stir-fry until everything is piping hot and then mix through the coriander.

Share the rice between your #bowls{} and spoon your sticky beef on top. Enjoy!

